<title type="html"><![CDATA[Conforming HTML 5 document]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=4059&amp;p=4854#p4854"><![CDATA[
Is it wrong, or is there the possible risk that it will be wrong (non-conforming) in the future, to use self-closing element tags like &lt;br /&gt; or ending tags like &lt;/p&gt; in a plain HTML 5 document?<br /><br />For example, from my XHTML 1 coding habits, all my basic documents look like very similar this:<br /><br />&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;<br />&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;<br />&lt;head&gt;<br />&lt;meta charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot; /&gt;<br />&lt;title&gt;This is an HTML document&lt;/title&gt;<br />&lt;/head&gt;<br />&lt;body&gt;<br />&lt;p&gt;Some&lt;br /&gt; text&lt;/p&gt;<br />&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;<br /><br />I do this because I put my code through an XML editor to catch when myself when I miss an &lt;/a&gt; tag for example. I <span style="font-style: italic">know</span> you can get away with not using those tags and still conform to the spec. But it's my preference right now to close everything.<br /><br />What's the consensus?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=458">Ritz</a> — Wed Mar 11, 2009 4:16 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
